docs.lead_paragraph: U.S. and Brazilian health workers seeking to determine if the Zika virus is causing a surge in birth defects ran into the chaotic reality of northeastern Brazil on their study's first day Tuesday. Traffic and logistical problems shredded their schedule, delaying or preventing meetings with mothers and babies.

docs.lead_paragraph: Even if infants appear normal at birth, they could later have problems like autism, bipolar disorder or schizophrenia, experts fear, based on similar infections.

headline.main: Zika May Increase Risk of Mental Illness, Researchers Say
headline.print_headline: The Potential Hidden Toll of Zika

docs.abstract: Researchers warn that children whose mothers were infected by Zika virus while pregnant, even those who appear unaffected by microcephaly at birth, may be at higher risk of mental health problems later in life; experts say virus resembles infectious agents linked to autism, bipolar disorder and schizophrenia.
